            <entry xml:id="entry_fætæg" xml:lang="os">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>fætæg</orth></form>
                <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>вождь</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>leader</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <abv:exampleGrp>
                    <abv:example>
                        <quote>ūcy ræstæǵy Iræn sæ fætæg wyd Alǧ˳yz</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>в то время вождем осетин был Алгуз</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>at that time the leader of the Ossetians was Alguz</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                    </abv:example>
                    <abv:example xml:lang="os-x-digor">
                        <usg><lang/></usg>
                        <quote>woʒænæj ældar wæ zingæ fætæg</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>алдар будет вашим знаменитым вождем</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>the aldar will be your famous leader</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Bes."/><biblScope>111</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                    <abv:example xml:lang="os-x-digor">
                        <usg><lang/></usg>
                        <quote>qazar læg næ zewi næ zajuj fætæg</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>ценный человек в нашей общей работе не остается вождем</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>a valuable person in our common work does not remain a leader</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Qazb."/><biblScope>35</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>*paϑaka-</w></mentioned>, от <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>рaϑ-</w>
                        <gloss><q>путь</q></gloss></mentioned>; собственно „путеводитель“. Ср.
                        <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>paϑ-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>path-, patha-</w>
                        <gloss><q>дорога</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>тропа</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"
                            ><w>pathaka-</w>
                        <gloss><q>путевед</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>путеводитель</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>πάτος</w>
                        <gloss><q>дорога</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>тропа</q></gloss></mentioned> и пр. В скифских диалектах были
                    представлены, по-видимому, все три варианта основы ‘путь’: 1. %ipanti-%i
                        (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/>
                        <w>Παντικαπης</w></mentioned>; <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                            /><biblScope>175</biblScope></bibl>), 2. %ipantā-%i (ос. <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_fændag"/>), 3. %iраϑ-%i (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/>
                        <w>Παταικος, Φιατακος</w></mentioned>, ос. <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_fætæg"/>; <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                            /><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>). %bСкиф.%b <mentioned
                        xml:lang="xsc"><lang/>
                        <w>*рaϑ-</w></mentioned> — вероятный источник германского слова для ‘тропы’:
                        <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/>
                        <w>Pfad</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="en"><lang/>
                        <w>path</w></mentioned> и пр.
                    (<bibl><biblScope>%sKluge%s</biblScope></bibl>). Несостоятельно сближение с
                        <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>pati-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>paiti-</w>
                        <gloss><q>господин</q></gloss></mentioned>
                            (<bibl><author>Stackelberg</author><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ZDMG"
                            /><biblScope>XLIII 672</biblScope></bibl>). Ср. <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_fændag"/>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                            /><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">Traces back to <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>*paϑaka-</w></mentioned>, from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>рaϑ-</w>
                        <gloss><q>path</q></gloss></mentioned>; ‘guide’ proper. Cf. <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>paϑ-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>path-, patha-</w>
                        <gloss><q>road</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>trail</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"
                            ><w>pathaka-</w>
                        <gloss><q>guide</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>guidebook</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>πάτος</w>
                        <gloss><q>road</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>trail</q></gloss></mentioned> etc. In the Scythian dialects,
                    apparently all three variants of the 'path' stem were represented: 1. %ipanti-%i
                        (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/>
                        <w>Παντικαπης</w></mentioned>; <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                            /><biblScope>175</biblScope></bibl>), 2. %ipantā-%i (Ossetic <ref
                        type="xr" target="#entry_fændag"/>), 3. %iраϑ-%i (<mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/>
                        <w>Παταικος, Φιατακος</w></mentioned>, Ossetic <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_fætæg"/>; <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                            /><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>). <mentioned xml:lang="xsc"><lang/>
                        <w>*рaϑ-</w></mentioned> is a likely source of the Germanic word for
                    ‘trail’: <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/>
                        <w>Pfad</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="en"><lang/>
                        <w>path</w></mentioned> etc. (<bibl><author>Kluge</author></bibl>). The
                    relation with <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>pati-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>paiti-</w>
                        <gloss><q>master</q></gloss></mentioned> is untenable
                            (<bibl><author>Stackelberg</author><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ZDMG"
                            /><biblScope>XLIII 672</biblScope></bibl>). Cf. <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_fændag"/>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"
                            /><biblScope>176</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
            </entry>
